  "text": "Grafana's configuration system is implemented in Go with a multi-layer architecture for loading, processing, and exposing configuration settings. Here's how the key components work together:\n\n## Configuration Loading Chain\n\n1. **INI File Parsing (pkg/setting/setting.go:963-1020)**\n   - The `loadConfiguration()` function orchestrates the entire configuration loading process\n   - First loads defaults from `conf/defaults.ini` using the gopkg.in/ini.v1 library\n   - Then applies configuration overrides in the following priority order:\n     - Command-line default properties (default.*)\n     - Custom INI file (conf/custom.ini)\n     - Environment variable overrides\n     - Command-line overrides (cfg:*)\n     - Variable expansion (environment variables and file references)\n\n2. **Default Values (conf/defaults.ini)**\n   - Grafana stores all default configuration values in `conf/defaults.ini`\n   - This file is loaded first and serves as the base configuration\n   - Custom configuration only needs to specify values that differ from defaults\n\n3. **Environment Variable Override Logic (pkg/setting/setting.go:744-759)**\n   - `applyEnvVariableOverrides()` checks for environment variables using the `EnvKey()` function\n   - The `EnvKey()` function (line 855-861) converts section and key names to the format `GF_SECTION_KEY`\n   - For example, `database.name` becomes `GF_DATABASE_NAME`\n   - Environment variables override values from the INI file\n\n4. **Variable Expansion (pkg/setting/expanders.go)**\n   - `expandConfig()` function processes configuration values containing variable references\n   - Supports two types of expanders:\n     - `envExpander`: Expands `$VARIABLE_NAME` or `${VARIABLE_NAME}` syntax to environment variable values\n     - `fileExpander`: Expands `$__file{/path/to/file}` syntax to read values from files\n   - Environment variable expansion for HOSTNAME has special handling for empty values\n\n5. **Command-Line Overrides (pkg/setting/setting.go:863-913)**\n   - `applyCommandLineDefaultProperties()` handles `cfg:default.*` arguments\n   - `applyCommandLineProperties()` handles `cfg:*` arguments\n   - Command-line arguments have the highest priority in the override chain\n\n## Configuration Sections with Defaults\n\nMultiple specialized configuration files handle different sections:\n- `setting_anonymous.go`: [auth.anonymous] section\n- `setting_auth_proxy.go`: [auth_proxy] section\n- `setting_azure.go`: [azure] and [auth.azuread] sections\n- `setting_smtp.go`: [smtp] section\n- `setting_jwt.go`: [auth.jwt] section\n- `setting_unified_alerting.go`: [unified_alerting] section\n- `setting_grpc.go`: [grpc_server] section\n- `setting_remote_cache.go`: [remote_cache] section\n- `setting_secrets_manager.go`: [secrets.management] section\nAnd many others, each reading default values using the `MustString()`, `MustBool()`, `MustDuration()` methods with sensible defaults\n\n## Sensitive Configuration Value Masking\n\n1. **RedactedValue Function (pkg/setting/setting.go:660-709)**\n   - Masks sensitive configuration values to prevent accidental exposure\n   - Applies regex patterns to identify sensitive keys containing:\n     - PASSWORD, SECRET, PRIVATE_KEY, CERTIFICATE, ENCRYPTION_KEY, TOKEN, API_TOKEN, etc.\n   - Returns `*********` (RedactedPassword constant) for matching sensitive keys\n   - Includes exceptions for analytics providers (RUDDERSTACK, APPLICATION_INSIGHTS, SENTRY)\n   - Falls back to URL redaction for values that appear to be URLs with credentials\n\n2. **API Settings Endpoint (pkg/api/admin.go:29-35)**\n   - `AdminGetSettings()` endpoint retrieves current settings from the configuration\n   - Calls `getAuthorizedSettings()` to filter settings based on user permissions\n   - Returns settings through the settings provider which applies `RedactedValue()` to mask sensitive data\n   - The provider's `Current()` method (pkg/setting/provider.go:118-129) creates a settings copy with redacted values\n\n3. **Settings Provider (pkg/setting/provider.go)**\n   - `OSSImpl.Current()` returns a `SettingsBag` (map[string]map[string]string) of all current settings\n   - Each value is passed through `RedactedValue()` with the full environment key name\n   - `OSSImpl.CurrentVerbose()` returns settings with source information (DB vs System)\n   - The provider enforces fine-grained access control via RBAC scopes: `settings:*`, `settings:SECTION:*`, `settings:SECTION:KEY`\n\n## Configuration Flow Summary\n\nThe configuration loading flow in `pkg/setting/setting.go:Load()` → `loadConfiguration()` is:\n1. Load defaults.ini\n2. Apply command-line default properties (cfg:default.*)\n3. Load and merge custom.ini\n4. Apply environment variable overrides (GF_* format)\n5. Apply command-line overrides (cfg:*)\n6. Expand variables in all values ($VAR, ${VAR}, $__file{path})\n7. Initialize logging and data paths\n8. Parse sections via specialized setting_*.go files\n\nWhen the `/api/admin/settings` endpoint is called, the current configuration is retrieved via `pkg/setting/provider.go:OSSImpl.Current()` which applies redaction before returning to the client, ensuring sensitive values like passwords, API tokens, and encryption keys are never exposed in the API response."
}

